  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and regulations aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- 40 recommendations providing a comprehensive framework\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides standards and guidance for preventing money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets international banking standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Mandatory regulations for EU member states\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Conduct risk assessments\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, with penalties for non-compliance.",
